</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" targetBox="[1744,1748,708,733]" targetPageId="93">
<paragraph blockId="93.[737,1331,2835,3253]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[737,913,3023,3056]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Distribution.</emphasis>
From WC Sonora to N 
<taxonomicName box="[738,840,3067,3096]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Sinaloa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sinaloa</taxonomicName>
states (NW Mexico).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="93.[737,1331,2835,3253]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[737,987,3102,3135]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 64-70 mm, tail 52-66 mm, ear 14-17 mm, hindfoot 16-17 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Sonoran Harvest
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="93.[125,1328,3259,3487]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
Mouse is small. Dorsum is ocherous buff, with black-tipped hairs along sides and rump; venter is white but plumbeous to bases. Feet are white, with fine dusky line. Tail is relatively long, 70-97% of head-body length, and has thin indistinct stripe. Skullis similar to that of the Plains Harvest Mouse (
<taxonomicName box="[736,909,3381,3410]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Ranunculus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montanus">R. montanus</taxonomicName>
), butit differs by having wider interorbital area, broader zygomatic process of maxilla, larger interorbital foramina, and longer nasals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1406,2614,311,733]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1408,1520,311,340]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Habitat.</emphasis>
Lowland (60-182 m) scrublands of mesquite (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1804" box="[2194,2300,311,340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Prosopis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Prosopis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[2318,2448,311,340]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) and other trees of the same legume family, grasses, and cultivated fields in Sonora and thorn scrub forests and in fields containing agaves (
<taxonomicName box="[2080,2161,386,419]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Agave" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Agave</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[2180,2379,386,419]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asparagaceae</taxonomicName>
), mesquite, and grasses in 
<taxonomicName box="[1550,1654,424,457]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae" genus="Sinaloa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sinaloa</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
